Histogram of Users’ Birthdays

Notes: http://flowingdata.com/2014/02/27/how-to-read-histograms-and-use-them-in-r/ - ggplot2 is easier to use than the plotting functions provided in ‘base’ pkg - qplot is really a histogram plot - scale_x_discrete() is used to separate out the bars to make it more viewable

# install.packages('ggplot2')
library(ggplot2)
qplot(data = pf, x = dob_day) +
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=1:31)

What are some things that you notice about this histogram?

Response: - We find that the graph is roughly uniform distributed for data. - The bar for 31 is smaller but expected since only 7 months in a year have 31 days. - The one bar that stands out is for 1st of the month. But this probably indicates we don’t have data for all subjects and the model defaulted to 1 in case of N/A.

Faceting

Notes: http://www.cookbook-r.com/Graphs/Facets_(ggplot2)/ - facet by dob_month; ncol is just how many graphs per column - This will basically break up histogram into 12, one per month

qplot(data = pf, x = dob_day) +
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=1:31) +
  facet_wrap(~dob_month, ncol = 3)

Be Skeptical - Outliers and Anomalies

Notes: - Important thing to note is which anamolies are actually real and which ones are due to some issue with data - Top coded data - Sometimes, data points whose values are above an upper bound are censored - In general, it is important to think about which category an anamoly falls into, so that it can be adjusted or discarded before analysis

Notes: - using na.omit(pf) instead will get rid of all observations that have NA in at least one variable - For this particular situation, might not be the best option - limits gives range of x axis - breaks states how often the ticks appear on the axis

Add a Scaling Layer

Notes: http://lightonphiri.org/blog/ggplot2-multiple-plots-in-one-graph-using-gridextra - ggplot is also quite similar to qplot except wrapping x and y args within aes - aes stands for aesthetic - note that scale_x_log10() and scale_x_sqrt() can be used w/ qplot() as well

library(gridExtra)
## Loading required package: grid
p1 <- qplot(data = pf, x = friend_count, binwidth = 20,
      xlab = 'user friend count', ylab = 'frequency of users per bin',
      color = I('black'), fill = I('#aa88ff')) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 3000), breaks = seq(0,3000, 200))
# Amazing how log10 plot transformed into a normal distribution!
p2 <- qplot(data = pf, x = log10(friend_count+1), binwidth = 0.1,
      xlab = 'log10(user friend count + 1)', ylab = 'frequency of users per bin',
      color = I('black'), fill = I('#aa88ff')) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 4), breaks = seq(0, 4, 0.5))

p3 <- qplot(data = pf, x = sqrt(friend_count), binwidth = 1,
      xlab = 'sqrt(user friend count)', ylab = 'frequency of users per bin',
      color = I('black'), fill = I('#aa88ff')) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 70), breaks = seq(10, 70, 10))

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, ncol = 1)

Frequency Polygons

Notes: - Uses the geom arg for qplot - notice how y is set to change to proportion rather than absolute to compare male and female

qplot(data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)), x = friend_count, y = ..count../sum(..count..), 
      binwidth = 20, geom = 'freqpoly',
      xlab = 'user friend count', ylab = 'frequency of users per bin',
      color = gender) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 3000), breaks = seq(0,3000, 200))

Box Plots

Notes: - Remember that y is always the frequency that you want to count - x is always what you want to divide by

qplot(data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)),
      x = gender, y = friend_count,
      geom = 'boxplot')

Adjust the code to focus on users who have friend counts between 0 and 1000.

Notes: - Although, we may think the solution is to subset the data to get rid of outliers above 1000, that will change the nature of the boxplot itself which is WRONG! - Note that scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000)) and ylim variable have the same problem as well! - Correct way is to use coord_cartesian() to only adjust the axis

# qplot(data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender) & friend_count <= 1000),
#      x = gender, y = friend_count,
#      geom = 'boxplot')
qplot(data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)),
      x = gender, y = friend_count,
      geom = 'boxplot') +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1000))

Getting Logical

Notes: - Important to change to factors to see summary for $mobile_checkins

summary(pf$mobile_likes)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     0.0     0.0     4.0   106.1    46.0 25110.0
summary(pf$mobile_likes > 0)
##    Mode   FALSE    TRUE    NA's 
## logical   35056   63947       0
mobile_checkins <- NA
pf$mobile_checkins <- ifelse(pf$mobile_likes > 0, 1, 0)
pf$mobile_checkins <- factor(pf$mobile_checkins)      
summary(pf$mobile_checkins)
##     0     1 
## 35056 63947
num <- sum(pf$mobile_checkins == 1)
den <- length((pf$mobile_checkins))
num * 100 / den
## [1] 64.59097

Response: *** Almost 65% of the users have used mobile checkins. This means that continuing to develop FB app for mobile platform is very important.
